    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay, that makes sense. so if the ph is locking out the nitrogen, is there like a way to tell if it's just being used up by the plants or if something else in the soil is actually causing the deficiency? like is there any sign of depletion or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the nitrogen is simply being used up, you will likely see progressive yellowing starting from the oldest, lowest leaves upwards as the plant prioritizes new growth. However, if a soil issue like high pH is causing the nutrient lockout, the deficiency signs will persist even after you replenish the fertilizer. Continuous testing and observing the pattern of yellowing (oldest leaves vs. new leaves) will help distinguish between depletion and unavailability.",
      "source": "target",
